{
  "texts": [
    "That is, for example, A ∈ PC(B) ⟺ B ∈ PC(A) where PC(B) denotes the parents and children of node B.",
    "However, errors made by CI tests can mean that local structures may not be symmetric in practice.",
    "Algorithms usually resolve these conflicts by applying the \"AND-rule\", where an edge will only be included in the global skeleton if the two nodes are in each other's parent-and-child sets.",
    "More sophisticated symmetry correction approaches can be used however-see, for example, Sect. 5.1.5.",
    "The Grow-Shrink (GS) algorithm (Margaritis and Thrun 1999) was the first to exploit the concept of a Markov Blanket to reduce the number of CI tests in the adjacency phase."
  ]
}